Checking Skewness¶

Plotting the distribution of the variables (skewness) of all the columns¶

In [11]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

cols = df_processed.columns

k = 0
plt.figure(figsize=(17, 28))

for col in cols:
    k = k + 1
    plt.subplot(7, 4, k)
    sns.distplot(df_processed[col])
    skewness = df_processed[col].skew()
    plt.title(col + ' Skewness: ' + str(skewness))
    
    # Print the skewness result
    if abs(skewness) < 0.5:
        print(f"{col} is not skewed (skewness = {skewness:.2f})")
    elif 0.5 <= abs(skewness) < 1:
        print(f"{col} is moderately skewed (skewness = {skewness:.2f})")
    else:
        print(f"{col} is highly skewed (skewness = {skewness:.2f})")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
from sklearn.utils import resample

# Separate the majority and minority classes
majority_class = credit_card_data[credit_card_data['Class'] == 0]
minority_class = credit_card_data[credit_card_data['Class'] == 1]

# Undersample the majority class
majority_undersampled = resample(majority_class,
                                replace=True,
                                n_samples=len(minority_class),
                                random_state=42)

# Combine the undersampled majority class with the minority class
undersampled_data = pd.concat([majority_undersampled, minority_class])

# Shuffle the data
undersampled_data = undersampled_data.sample(frac=1, random_state=42).reset_index(drop=True)

# Display the class distribution
print(undersampled_data['Class'].value_counts())
